<DOC><DOCNO> AP881212-0251 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 2121EST</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-YE--Science'88 Adv00   12-12 0317</FIRST><SECOND>BC-YE--Science '88, Adv 00,0347</SECOND><NOTE>$adv00</NOTE><NOTE>For Release in Year-End Editions</NOTE><HEAD>The Year's Top 10 Science Stories</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   These were some of the top science stories of 1988:</TEXT><HEAD>SUPERCONDUCTIVITY</HEAD><TEXT>   Researchers set a new high-temperature record, producingcompounds that became superconducting _ able to conduct electricitywithout resistance _ at 234 degrees below zero Fahrenheit.</TEXT><HEAD>GENETICS</HEAD><TEXT>   Researchers created a genetically engineered mouse with a humanimmune system, and a patent was awarded for the first time to agenetically engineered animal _ a mouse into which a cancer gene hadbeen inserted.</TEXT><HEAD>SPACE SHUTTLES</HEAD><TEXT>   The U.S. space shuttle program resumed and the Soviets launchedtheir own shuttle on its first mission.</TEXT><HEAD>GREENHOUSE EFFECT</HEAD><TEXT>   A summer drought across the United States led some scientists tosay that evidence of climatic changes produced by global warming _the so-called ``greenhouse effect'' _ is already being felt.</TEXT><HEAD>RADON</HEAD><TEXT>   The problem of radon gas in homes was recognized to be far morewidespread than previously believed, and the EPA estimated thatradon causes 20,000 deaths from lung cancer annually.</TEXT><HEAD>ABORTION PILL</HEAD><TEXT>   France approved the sale of an ``abortion pill,'' an anti-hormonethat interrupts pregnancy by blocking the implantation of afertilized egg on the uterine wall.</TEXT><HEAD>ASPIRIN AND HEART DISEASE</HEAD><TEXT>   A study of 22,071 male doctors showed that a single aspirin a daycan cut the risk of heart attacks almost in half.</TEXT><HEAD>AIDS</HEAD><TEXT>   A new, more accurate means of testing for AIDS was developed, butsome researchers expressed disappointment that more treatments forthe deadly disease had not yet been found.</TEXT><HEAD>SUPERCOLLIDER</HEAD><TEXT>   A building site was selected in Texas for the $4.4 billionsuperconducting super collider, bringing the world's largest atomsmasher a step closer to realization.</TEXT><HEAD>ASTRONOMY</HEAD><TEXT>   U.S. and Canadian astronomers reported the existence of 10planet-like objects orbiting distant stars, rekindling speculationabout the existence of life beyond Earth.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for Year-End Editions</NOTE></DOC>